0a4dc276-0c02-43e1-9212-48d167e6b71f.09437c7e-e534-43da-ac43-e1c275fe6a3f.description=
Clears the value of a flow variable

Input Parameters\:
keyName - the name of the flow variable to clear

Responses\:
success - cleared the flow variable

Scriptlet Example\:
[$scriptletContext putGlobal\: $keyName, null];
0a4dc276-0c02-43e1-9212-48d167e6b71f.188ab674-23d1-4631-be0a-1f482e760030.description=
This operation waits for the number of seconds specified in the "seconds" input.

Inputs\:
    seconds - The number of seconds to wait.

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the "completed sleep" message if the operation completed successfully and an error message otherwise. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

0a4dc276-0c02-43e1-9212-48d167e6b71f.79696f72-ee31-41fb-8608-482e981ec055.description=
Runs multiple Shell commands by creating a SSH shell and checking output against regular expressions.

Inputs\:
    host - The hostname/IP address of the target machine.
    port - The port number for SSH protocol.
Default value\: 22
    username - Name of the account on the target machine.
    password - The password for the username. When using a private key file or a private key string, this input will be used as the passphrase for the file or string. For security reasons it is recommend to provide this input and protect the private key when using the 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs.
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the remote machine.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default\: 8080. Valid values\: -1 and numbers greater than 0.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    privateKeyFile - Path to private key file (OpenSSH type) on the machine where is the worker. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    privateKeyData – A string representing the private key (OpenSSH type) used for authenticating the user. This string is usually the content of a private key file. The 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs are mutually exclusive. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    knownHostsPolicy - The policy used for managing known_hosts file. We recommend to use a "strict" policy so as to verify the host key against a local file containing known, trustworthy machines. If you choose "allow" or "add" policy then you will connect to the server without any verification. If there is a Man-In-The-Middle attack then you will be connected to a fake server and the SSH commands that you send will go through that fake server. 
Valid values\:  
allow\=It will permit the connection to any hosts. 
strict\=It will permit the connection only to the hosts specified in known_hosts file. 
add\=It will permit the connection to any hosts, if the host is not in the known_hosts file it will be added. 
Default value\: strict
    command - The commands to execute. This should be made up of 'send ' and 'expect ' statements separated by newlineCharacters.
    characterSet - The characterSet name for input stream encoding from the target machine.
Examples\: SJIS, EUC-JP, UTF-8
Default value\: UTF-8
    newlineCharacters - The character sequence to send as the enter key being pressed after each 'send' statement as the send expect script is processed in the command input. Either '\r\n' '\n' '\r' or a comma delimited list of ASCII escape sequences.
    timeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete.
Default value\: 90000
    connectTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the connection to be made.
Default value\: 10000
    sessionId - Identifier of a shared SSH shell session created by SSH Shell Logon. Instead of creating a new SSH shell session this one will be used if specified.

Results\:
    returnResult - The primary output.
    STDOUT - The standard output of the command(s).
    visualized - The output of the command in XML format.
    TimedOut - Is set to "true" if the value set in the "timeout" input has elapsed and the command timed out.

Responses\:
    success - The operation was executed successfully.
    failure - The connection could not be established or the commands are invalid for this operation (not for target machine's shell).

Notes\:
1. The following commands are supported\:
1.1. Send a Shell command.
    send 
Examples\: send ls
1.2. Send a char given by ASCII code.
    sendChar 
Examples\: sendChar 32
1.3. Match the entire previous command output against the regex.
    expect 
Examples\: expect (.*?)Desktop(.*)
1.4. The entire previous command output ends with the given text.
    expectEndsWith 
1.5. Match the last line from the previous command output against the regex.
    expectLastLine 
1.6. Fail on the success of the expect command\: expect, expectEndsWith or expectLastLine.
    errorOn 
1.7. If the expect command is successful then the operation will always execute the send command.
    always 
    on 
Examples\: 
Single line output\: always sendChar 121
                           on expect (.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
Multiple line output example 1\: always sendChar 121
                             	 on expect (?s)(.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
Multiple line output example 2\: always sendChar 121
                             	 on expectLastLine (.*?)Press y to continue(.*)
1.8. Use a different timeout for this send command\: send, sendChar.
    wait  
1.9. Use a different timeout for this expect command\: expect, expectEndsWith or expectLastLine.
    wait  
2. Hidden inputs\:
    knownHostsPath -  Specifies the path to the known_hots file on the running server.
Default value\: /.ssh/known_hosts
Examples\: /home/admin/.ssh/known_hosts
    readTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for reading and then matching the output with the regex from expect command.
Default value\: 20000
3. In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service.
4. The operation supports connections through HTTP proxy with username and password authentication.

0a4dc276-0c02-43e1-9212-48d167e6b71f.a85d9a12-8ce0-4e6f-9f09-e0a8d0e12912.description=
Uses Secure FTP (SFTP) to send a file on a RAS to a remote host.  

Inputs\:
host - IP address/host name.
port - The port to connect to on host.
username - Remote username.
password - Password to authenticate. If using a private key file this will be used as the passphrase for the file.
privateKey - Absolute path for private key file for public/private key authentication.
localFile - The path to the file on the RAS to be copied remotely using SFTP.
remoteLocation - The remote location where the file is to be placed.
characterSet - The name of the control encoding to use. Examples\: UTF-8, EUC-JP, SJIS.  Default is UTF-8.
closeSession - Close the SSH session at completion of operation?  Default value is true.  If false the SSH session can be reused by other SFTP commands in the same flow.  Valid values\: true, false.

Responses\:
success - Command completed successfully.
failure - Command failed.

Result\:
Local file will be copied to Remote system.
0a4dc276-0c02-43e1-9212-48d167e6b71f.aecd14ec-9f2c-4793-99b3-9d17a636586f.description=This operation iterates through a string that contains an array in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON). Each time this operation is called, it places the value of the current array element into the "returnResult" output and advances the iterator to the next array element. The JSON format is used to encode arrays and other values using JavaScript notation. For arrays, this means that the values need to be enclosed by square brackets, and each element in the array can be a string (enclosed by quotes), a number, true, false, null, or nested array or object. Commas are always used as delimiters between array elements, and they can also appear within string elements. The benefits of JavaScript arrays are that delimiters are fixed and cannot be confused with data, and that complex nesting of arrays and objects are supported. The description of the enclosing folder, /Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org. Inputs\: array - The JavaScript array that will be iterated through. A normal OO list is NOT a JavaScript array. Examples\: For example, the following is a simple JSON array\: [ "cat", "dog", "horse" ] The equivalent OO list (that is not a JavaScript array) is\: cat,dog,horse Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output and contains the current array element or an exception message if something went wrong. When incorporating this operation into a flow, you should assign a meaningful result value from this field. Result - This output field contains the value from the "returnResult" field. Responses\: has more - The iterator has not yet reached the end of the array. The "returnResult" output will be populated with the value of the current element in the array, and the iterator will advance to the next element in the array. no more - The iterator has reached the end of the array, and there is no more data to return. The iterator will become undefined after this call, which basically will reset it so that if called again, this operation will begin another iteration at the beginning of the array. failure - There was some error in iterating through the list, and the "returnResult" output will contain information about the error. This will occur if the input array is not a valid JavaScript array. You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with JavaScript Object Notation. Notes\: 1. Modifying the contents of the array during iteration is not generally supported, but will be safe as long as the affected item(s) are beyond the current position of the iterator. The iterator keeps track of where it is in the array by position. If items are added or removed to the list in a position preceding the iterator, it may cause the iterator to return results that are not obvious. For example, if the array contains [ "a", "b", "c" ] and the iterator is positioned on the second element, "b" and the first element is removed, then the iterator will now be at the last element in the list, "c". 2. There is currently a limitation that a flow can only have one of these array iterator steps active at a time without causing possible conflicts. In other words, if you need to iterate through a nested array, you should use a sub-flow to process the inner array. You may have two or more of these array iterators in the same flow as long as each iterator reaches the end of its array before the next one begins. 3. Note that since JavaScript arrays may contain nested arrays or other objects, the value returned in "returnResult" field may also require further processing. 0a4dc276-0c02-43e1-9212-48d167e6b71f.c2422a04-1384-4b29-9fd2-903d4c0eaca1.description=
